The sustainable way to heal and lose the “mom pooch” after having babies

1. Diaphragmatic breathing exercises & Kegels (consistently for the first 2 months) Most moms can start right after birth.

2. Maintain a small caloric deficit, including foods I enjoy. Eating at least 1800 - 2000 calories a day will allow you to maintain your milk supply- start tracking your daily calories. 

3. Deep floor & Pelvic floor workouts. If you want a stronger, more defined core, you have to rebuild all of your muscles from the inside out-starting with activating the TVA (your corset muscle). Quit doing sit ups & crunches and focus on movements like bird dog, overhead marches, heel taps etc

4. Slow, progressive strength training: Increasing the intensity or difficulty of workouts over time to promote development of muscle and strength. Keep in mind, not every workout you see online is postpartum safe, make sure you modify if needed. If you’re not sure how to start, join my postpartum program. 

5. Walking. Never underestimate the power of walking for fat loss. If you walk for 30 minutes and include enough activity throughout the day to reach the combined total of 10,000 steps, you can burn anywhere from 300 to 500 calories a day.

BACK FRIENDLY GLUTE WORKOUT 😇 Save it!

This was my first glute day in 3 months after my lower back injury. I’m SO happy to be back! If you experience back pain during lower body days try to use light weight and eliminate momentum, be slow and methodical. Avoid squats, instead focus on unilateral exercises and always include a dynamic total body warm-up. If you’re recovering from injury pls consult your doctor.

Workout & Tips: (3 sets x 10 reps)
•Reverse lunge (keep core engaged and hips tucked)
•Hip thrust/ Kas glute bridge (don’t go too low)
•Elevated glute bridge (use low elevation)
•Single leg RDL (good alternative to your regular deadlifts & RDLs, use proper form)
•Clamshell (only rotate from your hips, not your lower back)

Last slide is the most important step

Often people are disappointed to hear it took me a whole year to reach my goal after pregnancy. Healing your body, losing weight and building muscle takes time and you’ll have to take your body through phases. You can either be patient or torture yourself with unsustainable methods that will set you back.

REALISTIC POSTPARTUM RECOVERY TIMELINE:

Month 1-3: Recovery. Most women won’t be able to start training until after week 6 or 12. However there’s few exercises you can already start doing, like diaphragmatic breathing & kegels. Consult with your doctor.

Month 3-8: Core rehab & Weight loss. These next months focus on losing the pregnancy weight and healing Diastasis recti/ restrengthening your deep core muscles. You can achieve this by being in a caloric deficit (if you’re breastfeeding you can still be on a small deficit and maintain milk supply), doing deep core restoration exercises and following a progressive overload program 3-4 x a week. You can do it at home using dumbbells. 

Month 8-12: Muscle growth. Now that you’ve lost the pregnancy weight and healed your core, you may increase your calories to help build more muscle. You were most likely able to build some muscle the past months even through you were on a deficit, but now you can really focus on things like glute growth, or increasing your overall strength. The extra calories will make it A LOT easier!

•Urine leaking when you sneeze or cough.
